WEBVTT

00:04.004 --> 00:05.881
Oh, no. Maggie, you are burning up.

00:05.965 --> 00:08.175
And now you're on chemo for breast cancer.

00:08.259 --> 00:09.802
I'm going to be careful.

00:09.885 --> 00:11.512
Oh, I'm sorry. I thought I had a patient.

00:11.595 --> 00:14.265
Crockett Marcel, fourth year, surgery.

00:14.348 --> 00:16.726
Welcome back. And the concussion?

00:16.809 --> 00:18.352
Yeah, I'm taking it slowly.

00:18.436 --> 00:21.522
I just have to ask. Do you love him?

00:21.605 --> 00:22.648
My relationship with Phillip

00:22.732 --> 00:25.025
is the only thing in my life
that's working right now.

00:25.109 --> 00:28.904
My lymphoma is progressing
and there's nothing more they can do.

00:28.988 --> 00:31.031
I want to be there. For all of it.

00:33.367 --> 00:34.618
Egg whites...

00:36.162 --> 00:37.413
Whoa.
(CHUCKLING)

00:37.496 --> 00:39.832
What's all this?
It's a meringue.

00:40.666 --> 00:42.918
For breakfast?
No, it's for Robin's birthday.

00:43.002 --> 00:44.545
It's for a Baked Alaska.

00:44.628 --> 00:45.796
The meringue goes over

00:45.880 --> 00:46.922
the ice cream and the cake.

00:47.673 --> 00:48.716
But Robin's birthday

00:48.799 --> 00:49.884
isn't for a couple of weeks though, right?

00:49.967 --> 00:51.635
Yeah. This is a test run.

00:51.719 --> 00:53.304
Oh.
(CHUCKLING)

00:53.387 --> 00:55.139
What's the fire extinguisher for?

00:55.931 --> 00:57.141
I'm gonna set it on fire.

00:58.225 --> 00:59.769
Hey, how do you keep
the ice cream from melting?

00:59.852 --> 01:01.312
That's what the test run's for.

01:01.395 --> 01:03.147
Ah.
Wait a minute.

01:03.230 --> 01:04.565
Maybe I should play hooky today.

01:05.274 --> 01:07.067
Stay home. Be your official taster.

01:10.404 --> 01:11.655
(CRASHING)
CAROLINE: Ow!

01:13.407 --> 01:14.742
CeCe?
Ow! Oh, my gosh.

01:14.825 --> 01:16.285
Whoa.
Honey.

01:16.368 --> 01:17.703
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
What happened?

01:18.537 --> 01:20.206
I'm getting so clumsy, honey.

01:20.289 --> 01:22.082
Let me look. Let me...
No, no. Please, please. Please.

01:22.166 --> 01:25.294
All right. Learned this one in biophysics.

01:25.377 --> 01:26.378
Yeah.

01:27.463 --> 01:29.840
(BLOWING)

01:29.924 --> 01:32.176
Stop it.
That's actually pretty cool.

01:32.259 --> 01:33.886
It's all in the lips, ladies.

01:33.969 --> 01:36.055
I bet.
Hey.

01:36.722 --> 01:38.265
Looks like we're paired together today.

01:39.767 --> 01:40.768
Lucky me.

01:41.769 --> 01:42.770
Excuse me.

01:45.648 --> 01:49.819
So, babe. That Crockett guy
is working days now?

01:49.902 --> 01:51.111
What's the deal with him?

01:51.195 --> 01:52.613
Not sure he's my speed.

01:52.696 --> 01:54.907
Strikes me as someone
who doesn't take things seriously.

01:54.990 --> 01:55.991
Yeah.

01:57.743 --> 01:59.787
Doctor Choi.
Yeah?

01:59.870 --> 02:00.871
Treatment Four.

02:01.622 --> 02:02.623
Mags?
Uhâ€“huh.

02:02.706 --> 02:04.708
Todd Shepard?
Doesn't say what he's in here for.

02:05.209 --> 02:06.710
Said he wanted to
discuss it with a doctor.

02:09.839 --> 02:12.591
No, I'm in the ED now.
Treatment Room Four.

02:13.592 --> 02:14.593
How far away are you guys?

02:16.262 --> 02:17.763
You're positive you'll be here
within the hour?

02:19.056 --> 02:20.307
Right. Thanks.

02:21.600 --> 02:22.893
Sorry, I really needed to make that call.

02:22.977 --> 02:24.144
That's okay, Todd.

02:24.228 --> 02:25.813
I go by Shep, if you don't mind.

02:25.896 --> 02:27.815
Okay, Shep. I'm Dr. Choi.

02:27.898 --> 02:28.983
What brings you in today?

02:29.900 --> 02:32.444
About six weeks ago,
I was diagnosed with GBM.

02:32.528 --> 02:33.529
It's a terminal...

02:33.612 --> 02:35.155
Terminal brain cancer.

02:35.239 --> 02:36.240
I'm sorry, Shep.

02:36.323 --> 02:39.243
I've got all my medical records right here
in case you're interested.

02:39.326 --> 02:41.328
Are you experiencing any complications?

02:41.412 --> 02:44.248
Not exactly. Excuse me, one second.

02:48.002 --> 02:49.545
(SIGHS)

02:49.628 --> 02:53.507
The phone call I just made
was to a company called CCI.

02:53.591 --> 02:54.925
Camden Cryonics Institute.

02:55.801 --> 02:58.429
They're gonna preserve me until
a cure can be found for my condition.

02:58.512 --> 02:59.513
They're on the way here now.

02:59.597 --> 03:00.681
To freeze you?

03:01.640 --> 03:05.060
Um, it's called vitrification. But, yeah.

03:05.144 --> 03:07.813
You understand you have to be
declared dead first.

03:08.439 --> 03:09.440
That's why I'm here.

03:10.316 --> 03:12.359
For you to declare me dead, so to speak.

03:13.986 --> 03:16.614
I'm sorry, Shep, I'm confused.

03:19.658 --> 03:23.037
The cocktail I've been drinking
contains amitriptyline,

03:23.120 --> 03:26.999
lorazepam and two hundred milligrams
of amphetamines.

03:27.082 --> 03:28.959
It should put me to sleep
in a little over an hour

03:29.043 --> 03:32.129
and arrest my heart sufficiently
for you to declare me dead in about five.

03:33.672 --> 03:35.841
I have a D.N.I. and D.N.R.
My lawyer assures me it's all in order.

03:35.925 --> 03:37.384
Doris! Come here,
we gotta pump his stomach.

03:37.468 --> 03:39.053
Stop! I refuse treatment!

03:39.136 --> 03:40.137
Don't listen to him, Doris.
SHEP: Help! Assault!

03:40.220 --> 03:41.972
Give me the tube.
This doctor keeps touching me,

03:42.056 --> 03:45.935
I'll sue the whole lot of you!
Dr. Choi. Stop.

03:56.820 --> 03:58.989
Well, here you can see the fracture
of the distal radius.

03:59.073 --> 04:00.115
Minimal displacement.

04:00.783 --> 04:03.744
CeCe, are you all right?
Maggie said you took some kind of fall...

04:03.827 --> 04:05.371
Broke her wrist.

04:05.454 --> 04:06.705
My arms aren't as long as they used to be.

04:06.789 --> 04:09.500
I've seen worse. Four to six weeks
in a cast, you'll be fine.

04:09.583 --> 04:11.919
What? Four to six weeks?
Well, wait a minute.

04:12.670 --> 04:14.672
I need to be able to use my arm.

04:14.755 --> 04:16.674
Isn't there another operation we can do?

04:17.549 --> 04:19.551
Normally, yeah,
we would surgically insert a plate.

04:19.635 --> 04:20.970
Shorten your recovery time,

04:21.053 --> 04:22.638
but I really wouldn't
recommend that, Mrs. Charles.

04:22.721 --> 04:23.722
Why?

04:23.806 --> 04:26.266
You'd just open the door to a whole host
of other complications

04:26.350 --> 04:28.352
given your condition, babe.
It's just not worth it.

04:28.435 --> 04:29.937
They're right, CeCe.

04:30.020 --> 04:32.147
Let's just let ortho put a cast on it.

04:32.231 --> 04:33.649
It's the least worst option.

04:33.732 --> 04:34.775
Right?

04:34.858 --> 04:36.318
Hey, I'll go talk to the attending.

04:36.402 --> 04:37.861
Thank... Wait a minute.

04:37.945 --> 04:39.655
You okay, CeCe?

04:39.738 --> 04:41.323
She wants to make
a Baked Alaska for Robin.

04:41.407 --> 04:44.284
It was a flambe. I was making her
a flambe for her birthday.

04:44.368 --> 04:47.329
Okay. I'll go to the bakery.
I'll get a big old cake...

04:47.413 --> 04:50.082
No way.
Sparklers. And we'll do it up nice.

04:50.165 --> 04:51.166
All right?

04:51.250 --> 04:54.545
Daniel, I hate to pull you away
but we've got a situation.

04:54.628 --> 04:56.046
It's fine. You can go. Go.
Okay?

04:56.130 --> 04:57.464
It's fine. I'm fine.
I'll be right back.

04:57.548 --> 04:59.258
I'm fine. I'm fine.
All right, ya all right?

05:02.052 --> 05:04.555
He's committing suicide right in front
of us, how's this a grey area?

05:04.638 --> 05:07.808
Well, it's complicated,
due to his condition and his prognosis.

05:07.891 --> 05:11.228
Have you had a chance to review
Mr. Shepard's medical records, Sam?

05:11.311 --> 05:13.397
Yeah, he's terminal.

05:13.480 --> 05:16.734
I mean, I could go in and do a resection
and aggressively radiate but it...

05:16.817 --> 05:18.694
It'd buy him 12 to 15 months, tops.

05:18.777 --> 05:20.904
It's a question of "when"
and not "if" with this guy.

05:20.988 --> 05:22.865
And Mr. Shepard has the right
to refuse treatment.

05:22.948 --> 05:24.575
He's just a kid.
Not according to the law.

05:24.658 --> 05:27.828
He's 18. He's talking about
freezing his brain, for Christ's sakes.

05:27.911 --> 05:29.621
He thinks he's living
in some kind of comic book.

05:29.705 --> 05:32.207
Well, where are we with cryonics, Sam?

05:32.291 --> 05:34.752
I mean, is it possible
to freeze the brain?

05:34.835 --> 05:37.463
Yeah, sort of, but that's the easy part.

05:37.546 --> 05:39.715
Hard part's thawing it out again
and having it still work.

05:39.798 --> 05:41.759
And that ain't even close to happening.

05:41.842 --> 05:44.011
Miss Goodwin, I need to lavage
this kid's stomach right now

05:44.094 --> 05:45.637
or else the drugs'll
get into his bloodstream

05:45.721 --> 05:46.805
and we'll be forced
to use supportive measures.

05:46.889 --> 05:49.725
No, no. Mr. Shepard has a D.N.I.
and a D.N.R., Dr. Choi.

05:49.808 --> 05:51.852
So, unless the hospital
deems him incapable of

05:51.935 --> 05:54.229
making an informed decision,
we have to honor his wishes.

05:55.189 --> 05:59.026
All right, so let's ascertain
Mr. Shepard's decisional capacity

05:59.109 --> 06:00.486
and then go from there.

06:00.569 --> 06:03.072
Uh, Daniel? Daniel?

06:03.155 --> 06:04.615
Yeah.
Mr. Shepard?

06:04.698 --> 06:06.492
Yes. I will talk to him.

06:06.575 --> 06:08.577
How long before he starts
to lose consciousness?

06:08.660 --> 06:09.912
Forty, 45 minutes.

06:14.708 --> 06:16.126
MAGGIE: Sharon, a word please.

06:18.337 --> 06:20.172
Why is there someone
named Paula over there

06:20.255 --> 06:21.673
saying that she's here to shadow me?

06:21.757 --> 06:22.758
Oh!

06:22.841 --> 06:23.842
Maggie, I'm sorry.

06:23.926 --> 06:26.512
I intended to speak with you
about that first.

06:26.595 --> 06:30.099
For the next few weeks,
Paula is going to be your new orientee.

06:30.182 --> 06:32.810
Considering how much
you have on your plate.

06:32.893 --> 06:35.437
Sharon, really, I feel great.

06:35.521 --> 06:37.940
Don't you feel worn down from your chemo?
No!

06:38.023 --> 06:40.984
And you're happy
with your oncologist at East Mercy?

06:41.068 --> 06:43.070
They're treating me fine, Sharon.

06:43.153 --> 06:45.155
And no one here knows anything.
But if I've got someone

06:45.239 --> 06:48.200
shadowing me around, people here
are gonna start asking questions.

06:48.283 --> 06:50.619
It's too late. Paula's yours.

06:50.702 --> 06:52.162
But I just...
Humor me.

07:00.254 --> 07:02.256
Hello, Keisha. Hi.
Hi.

07:02.339 --> 07:04.341
I'm Dr. Manning. I hear you hurt your leg?

07:04.424 --> 07:08.095
She tripped and fell carrying a cup
of hot water for me out of the microwave.

07:08.178 --> 07:09.680
Spilled all over her leg.

07:09.763 --> 07:12.850
I'm sorry to hear that.
How about I take a look, all right?

07:14.351 --> 07:15.477
All right, let's see.

07:16.228 --> 07:18.480
(KEISHA WHIMPERING)

07:19.648 --> 07:21.817
Two to three percent
superficial partial thickness

07:21.900 --> 07:23.193
on the left anterior thigh.

07:23.277 --> 07:24.653
MONIQUE: Mmmâ€“hmm.

07:25.237 --> 07:26.613
She has a second degree burn.

07:26.697 --> 07:27.906
Oh, my God.

07:27.990 --> 07:30.492
But it should be able to heal on its own
without surgery,

07:30.576 --> 07:32.286
but it will take a few weeks.

07:32.369 --> 07:34.454
I'm gonna do a quick scrub bedside
just to speed up the process.

07:35.122 --> 07:36.456
Will you start her on an IV?

07:36.540 --> 07:38.000
MRS. JONES: Is it gonna hurt her?
No.

07:38.083 --> 07:40.794
I will give Keisha sedation.
She won't feel a thing.

07:40.878 --> 07:43.422
Thank you for being so still, Keisha.

07:43.505 --> 07:45.382
You are a very brave girl.

07:46.925 --> 07:48.218
All right, I'll be back shortly.

07:48.927 --> 07:49.928
Hey, good job.

07:53.098 --> 07:54.933
Hey, guys.
PHILLIP: Hi.

07:55.017 --> 07:57.477
What are you doing here?
I thought you were headed to the park?

07:57.561 --> 08:00.898
Well, we were, but we were
putting some snacks together,

08:00.981 --> 08:03.775
and we figured you might get hungry,
so, we thought we'd stop by.

08:03.859 --> 08:04.860
Whatcha got?

08:04.943 --> 08:05.944
It's a cookie.

08:06.028 --> 08:08.030
(GASPS) It's a cookie!
It's a cookie!

08:08.113 --> 08:09.907
(LAUGHING)
Aw!

08:09.990 --> 08:12.492
Thank you. I'm gonna eat it
with my lunch, okay?

08:12.576 --> 08:13.785
Okay.
Okay.

08:13.869 --> 08:15.787
Well, why don't we let Mommy
get back to work?

08:15.871 --> 08:16.872
I'll see you.
Bye.

08:18.540 --> 08:21.001
All right. Let's head on out.

08:22.294 --> 08:24.004
(GASPS) Oh, hey.

08:24.838 --> 08:25.839
Don't work too hard.

08:26.715 --> 08:28.967
You see this door?
We're gonna walk through this door here...

08:30.052 --> 08:32.387
WILL: Owen's getting so big.

08:32.471 --> 08:33.472
Yeah.

08:35.057 --> 08:37.017
Yeah, so, listen,
I've been doing some research

08:37.100 --> 08:39.186
on postâ€“traumatic injury rehabilitation

08:39.269 --> 08:42.356
and there's this computerized
training program funded by the Pentagon

08:42.439 --> 08:44.399
that's had some early success.

08:44.483 --> 08:45.859
Now, it's not on the market yet,

08:45.943 --> 08:48.487
but Abrams says there's
a beta version upstairs you can try out.

08:49.821 --> 08:51.531
It might help you get your memory back.

08:51.615 --> 08:53.909
Keisha's ready to be debrided.

08:53.992 --> 08:55.953
Thanks. Will you hook her up
to the monitors

08:56.036 --> 08:57.287
and prep her for five milligrams

08:57.371 --> 08:58.664
of etomidate.
Mmmâ€“hmm.

08:58.747 --> 09:01.124
And I can forward you
the details on that program if you like.

09:02.084 --> 09:03.085
Sure.

09:05.921 --> 09:09.466
This outfit that you've contracted
with, uh, CCI?

09:09.549 --> 09:10.717
Uhâ€“huh.

09:10.801 --> 09:14.638
They're gonna store you indefinitely
with the hope that in the future,

09:14.721 --> 09:15.931
there'll be a cure for the cancer

09:16.014 --> 09:17.099
that you have?
Yeah.

09:18.475 --> 09:19.476
Well, it sounds expensive.

09:20.686 --> 09:22.396
I inherited some money when Gramps died.

09:23.438 --> 09:24.439
Enough to cover it.

09:24.523 --> 09:27.234
Mmmâ€“hmm. It is pretty farâ€“out stuff, Shep.

09:27.317 --> 09:30.445
You discussed any of this
with your family?

09:34.616 --> 09:35.826
I tried.

09:35.909 --> 09:37.244
Yeah.

09:37.327 --> 09:40.372
They don't... They don't get it?
They don't understand?

09:43.458 --> 09:44.459
Look.

09:45.294 --> 09:47.212
You're here to determine
whether I'm sane enough

09:47.296 --> 09:49.881
to make a decision like this, aren't you?

09:49.965 --> 09:51.300
Yeah.

09:51.383 --> 09:52.384
Here's a hypothetical.

09:53.218 --> 09:55.012
If the hospital across
the street could cure me,

09:55.971 --> 09:58.223
wouldn't you feel ethically compelled
to send me there for treatment?

09:59.308 --> 10:00.517
I would.

10:00.600 --> 10:01.601
Well, that's what I'm doing.

10:02.602 --> 10:04.730
Sending myself to a better hospital.

10:04.813 --> 10:07.149
Only the hospital I'm going to
is in the future.

10:08.358 --> 10:10.235
Have you really thought about
what that future looks like?

10:11.236 --> 10:15.490
I mean, it won't be recognizable.
You won't recognize yourself.

10:17.117 --> 10:20.871
You're trading away, potentially,
a year of your life.

10:20.954 --> 10:24.124
I mean, that's something priceless,
for a huge unknown.

10:24.207 --> 10:25.500
I mean, you understand that, right?

10:27.711 --> 10:30.172
Shep? Shep?

10:30.255 --> 10:31.923
Look, if we're gonna keep you alive,

10:32.007 --> 10:34.676
if you're having any second thoughts,
we need to know that now.

10:36.928 --> 10:38.430
You know the Apollo astronauts?

10:40.599 --> 10:42.309
Those rockets were
just as likely to blow up

10:42.392 --> 10:44.478
as they were to propel them into space.

10:46.355 --> 10:48.190
And the calculations made
to bring them home?

10:50.317 --> 10:51.985
They were done with pencil and paper.

10:54.279 --> 10:56.865
Those astronauts had wives

10:56.948 --> 11:00.118
and kids and lives to live.

11:03.163 --> 11:05.415
You'd have had to been crazy to climb into
one of those capsules,

11:07.667 --> 11:08.668
don't you think?

11:17.969 --> 11:18.970
So?

11:20.055 --> 11:22.557
Finding somebody doesn't have the capacity

11:22.641 --> 11:24.393
to make an informed decision,
I mean, it's...

11:24.476 --> 11:26.103
It's a high hurdle, Ethan.
He's committing suicide.

11:26.186 --> 11:28.772
He's a danger to himself by definition.
Just put him on a psych hold.

11:28.855 --> 11:31.858
Yeah, but if you follow his logic, he's...
He's not committing suicide.

11:31.942 --> 11:34.152
He's, like, doing precisely the opposite.

11:34.236 --> 11:36.863
He's kinda remarkably clearâ€“headed about
the whole thing.

11:36.947 --> 11:40.158
Then what about the medications
he's taking for the GBM?

11:40.242 --> 11:42.577
The steroids, the antiâ€“convulsives.

11:42.661 --> 11:44.621
Those have been known to alter
someone's personality, right?

11:44.704 --> 11:47.416
Yeah, but I mean, we...
We don't have a baseline to compare it to.

11:47.499 --> 11:50.836
A determination like that at this point
would be entirely subjective.

11:50.919 --> 11:53.088
His parents are on their way, Dr. Charles.

11:55.674 --> 11:57.634
Maybe they'll get here in time
to say goodbye to their son.

12:00.762 --> 12:05.142
Hey, Dan. Hey, it's Caroline.
She's insistent on having surgery.

12:05.225 --> 12:07.853
I couldn't talk her out of it.
She's up in ortho.

12:10.730 --> 12:11.857
Help!

12:14.067 --> 12:15.360
My baby stopped breathing!

12:17.529 --> 12:18.530
Oh...

12:19.406 --> 12:20.949
Get help, we got a newborn!

12:21.575 --> 12:23.577
Baghdad! Let's go!

12:23.660 --> 12:24.786
On the move, excuse me!

12:26.163 --> 12:29.666
NURSE: Okay, step in, close the glass.
Cyanotic and unresponsive.

12:29.749 --> 12:31.960
Let's get her on the monitors
and start bagging.

12:32.043 --> 12:35.547
NURSE: Right away, Doctor.
Deep lac on the left anterior chest.

12:35.630 --> 12:37.632
Are you the mom?
Yes. Yes, I am.

12:37.716 --> 12:40.427
What's your name?
Nicole. Is she gonna be okay?

12:40.510 --> 12:42.012
Can you tell me what happened, Nicole?

12:42.095 --> 12:45.140
I was driving to pick up
some groceries, you know,

12:45.223 --> 12:47.058
and all of a sudden,
the contractions started,

12:47.142 --> 12:49.060
like out of nowhere.
Wait a second, you were just in labor?

12:49.144 --> 12:51.396
You delivered the baby yourself?
In the back seat of my car.

12:51.480 --> 12:54.566
That was an accident...
I was cutting the umbilical cord.

12:54.649 --> 12:57.235
NURSE: Can you get a line in?
I was supposed to do that, wasn't I?

12:57.319 --> 12:58.403
That's right.

12:58.487 --> 13:00.655
Heart rate's coming back up.
Yeah, she's still not breathing.

13:00.739 --> 13:03.867
I need to intubate.
Somebody get me a neonatal pack.

13:03.950 --> 13:06.411
I can't believe you're even standing.
Come on, let's get you looked at.

13:06.495 --> 13:09.748
I'm not leaving him!
Nicole, it's a girl.

13:12.042 --> 13:14.002
Come on. You've lost a lot of blood.
No!

13:14.085 --> 13:15.253
Let her stay, Sexton.

13:16.254 --> 13:17.255
Tube.

13:18.924 --> 13:21.968
I'm in. Bag and call neonatology.
You got it.

13:23.386 --> 13:24.888
Can someone get a chair for Mom here?

13:29.809 --> 13:31.728
I'm afraid, Mommy!
It's okay, baby.

13:31.811 --> 13:33.897
The doctor said it wasn't going to hurt.
That's right, Keisha.

13:34.648 --> 13:36.650
Now, you may feel a little drowsy
from the medication.

13:36.733 --> 13:37.776
It's okay to close your eyes
and go to sleep.

13:38.652 --> 13:39.653
Monique?

13:40.779 --> 13:43.073
She's a little hypotensive.
Is it okay to proceed?

13:43.156 --> 13:45.200
BP?
Ninetyâ€“six over sixty.

13:46.076 --> 13:47.077
That's not too low.

13:47.160 --> 13:48.995
She's probably just dehydrated.
Push the meds.

13:49.079 --> 13:51.248
She's been complaining
about feeling lethargic

13:51.331 --> 13:52.666
for a couple of weeks now.

13:52.749 --> 13:54.876
Her pediatrician
couldn't find anything wrong.

13:55.919 --> 13:58.129
I've been getting on her lately,
for being so lazy.

13:58.797 --> 14:00.298
(ALARM BLARING)
(LABORED BREATHING)

14:00.382 --> 14:01.716
What's going on?

14:01.800 --> 14:03.051
She's seizing.
Mmmâ€“hmm.

14:03.134 --> 14:04.302
Push one of Ativan!

14:05.178 --> 14:06.763
BP's crashing. Sixty over forty.

14:06.846 --> 14:09.307
Bolus 500 milliliters of normal saline.

14:09.391 --> 14:11.476
Keisha? Talk to me!
NURSE: Ma'am?

14:11.560 --> 14:13.144
I'm gonna need you to move over here.

14:13.228 --> 14:14.688
I need to intubate. Draw up 50 of sux.

14:14.771 --> 14:16.273
What's happening with my little girl?

14:23.488 --> 14:24.656
Your phone connects to the CarePoint

14:24.739 --> 14:26.116
you're using, right?
Uhâ€“huh.

14:26.199 --> 14:27.617
I'm superâ€“familiar with it.

14:27.701 --> 14:29.828
FYI, got my MICN certification last year.

14:29.911 --> 14:33.248
So whenever you're ready for me to do
an incoming call, I can...

14:33.331 --> 14:34.416
You know what would be really helpful?

14:35.584 --> 14:37.586
You checking
all the drug expiration dates.

14:39.087 --> 14:40.422
The drug expirations?

14:40.505 --> 14:43.633
Yeah, there are dates stamped
on every package.

14:43.717 --> 14:45.677
You can start with the Pyxis over there,
and then of course,

14:46.636 --> 14:47.721
all the crash carts.

14:48.388 --> 14:51.766
Okeyâ€“dokey.
Yeah. Okeyâ€“dokey.

14:54.394 --> 14:55.979
The girl's sedated on a vent?
Mmmâ€“hmm.

14:57.355 --> 14:59.190
Any idea what caused her to crash?

14:59.274 --> 15:01.443
Apparently, Keisha fell
when she burned herself.

15:01.526 --> 15:03.862
Maybe she bumped her head
and caused an epidural bleed?

15:03.945 --> 15:05.614
Well, walk me through what you know.
Maybe I can help.

15:06.239 --> 15:08.742
So, the mother said Keisha ran a bit
of a fever last week.

15:08.825 --> 15:11.453
But the pediatrician couldn't find
anything out of the ordinary.

15:11.536 --> 15:14.080
She was a little hypotensive
when I had Monique push the ketamine,

15:14.164 --> 15:15.957
but nothing to precipitate this...

15:16.041 --> 15:18.376
Ketamine? You mean etomidate, right?

15:19.336 --> 15:20.337
What?

15:20.920 --> 15:23.632
You had Monique push etomidate.
I heard you call it earlier.

15:23.715 --> 15:24.924
Yeah. It's right here in the chart.

15:26.926 --> 15:30.847
That's strange. I don't...
I don't know how I confused those two.

15:32.390 --> 15:35.560
Whatever, it doesn't matter,
there's no real clinical difference.

15:35.644 --> 15:37.270
You feeling all right, Nat?

15:37.354 --> 15:38.563
Any headaches or problems concentrating...

15:38.647 --> 15:39.856
I misspoke, Will.

15:39.939 --> 15:41.316
Let's not make a big deal out of it.

15:55.205 --> 15:56.998
What did you put in her side there?

15:57.707 --> 15:59.751
Well, your daughter's got
a collapsed lung.

15:59.834 --> 16:01.419
That tube's gonna help her breathe.

16:01.503 --> 16:03.546
So, how long until I'll be able
to get her out of here?

16:03.630 --> 16:06.549
It's gonna be a while. It'll be okay.

16:09.844 --> 16:11.137
Have you thought of a name yet?

16:11.221 --> 16:12.305
Not really.

16:13.348 --> 16:14.724
Okay, you don't need to do this right now,

16:14.808 --> 16:17.018
but before you leave you're gonna need
to fill out these forms,

16:17.102 --> 16:18.353
for the birth certificate.

16:20.105 --> 16:23.483
And we need to let your OB know
that you delivered already.

16:24.401 --> 16:25.777
If you give me a name...

16:25.860 --> 16:27.362
No, I didn't really have an OB.

16:28.947 --> 16:30.323
I mean, I had one,

16:30.407 --> 16:33.702
but they were all the way across town
near where the baby's father lives,

16:33.785 --> 16:35.537
and we recently split, so...

16:35.620 --> 16:37.372
Oh, I'm sorry.

16:39.165 --> 16:41.126
Here. I'll fill out as much as I can.

16:41.960 --> 16:43.420
Oh, your hand.

16:43.503 --> 16:45.130
Melissa, may I have some gauze, please?

16:51.177 --> 16:53.888
You know, I can't do any more than this
without getting you admitted.

16:53.972 --> 16:55.932
It's okay, I'm all right.

16:56.015 --> 16:57.684
You need to see a doctor,

16:57.767 --> 17:01.187
if for no other reason than to make sure
you've passed all your placenta.

17:01.271 --> 17:03.481
Dr. Marcel? Isn't that right?

17:03.565 --> 17:06.151
Please, don't separate me from my baby.

17:06.234 --> 17:07.610
She needs me with her.

17:07.694 --> 17:10.447
Hey.
How about we just get you registered?

17:10.530 --> 17:11.906
That way we can get you
out of these clothes

17:11.990 --> 17:13.700
and into something more comfortable.

17:13.783 --> 17:14.951
Then you can stay here with your child.

17:15.034 --> 17:17.537
Okay. Thank you.

17:17.620 --> 17:19.038
April here will scare you up some scrubs.

17:25.920 --> 17:28.423
I'm sorry, Dr. Marcel?
Mmmâ€“hmm.

17:28.506 --> 17:30.049
She really needs to be examined.

17:30.133 --> 17:33.803
Oh, relax, Sexton.
We just saved a baby's life.

17:33.887 --> 17:35.263
That's good news.

17:35.346 --> 17:37.599
Look, something seems off with Mom.

17:37.682 --> 17:38.850
Why's she so resistant
to being seen by a doctor?

17:38.933 --> 17:39.934
(SIGHS)

17:40.018 --> 17:42.729
Who knows? Maybe she took
a little somethingâ€“something

17:42.812 --> 17:44.272
to get her through the birth
and now she's afraid

17:44.355 --> 17:46.024
of having her baby taken away.

17:46.107 --> 17:48.443
I don't know. And neither do you.

17:48.526 --> 17:53.364
But if she didn't just deliver this baby,
it's our responsibility to find out.

17:53.448 --> 17:56.826
Maybe we could figure out a way
to draw her blood, check her HCG levels...

17:56.910 --> 17:57.911
Oh!

17:58.745 --> 18:02.332
You draw anyone's blood without consent,
that's considered assault.

18:02.415 --> 18:04.918
Now, I don't know about you,
but I like being a doctor.

18:05.001 --> 18:06.002
And not going to jail.

18:06.628 --> 18:09.214
If you won't help me,
I'll call DCFS in to interview her.

18:11.174 --> 18:13.676
Nicole's a righty, by the way.
So?

18:14.511 --> 18:18.389
So, if she actually injured her hand
while cutting the umbilical cord,

18:18.473 --> 18:21.226
wouldn't it more likely be
the free hand that got cut?

18:26.940 --> 18:28.608
Hey.
Hey.

18:28.691 --> 18:30.068
So, what's up?

18:30.151 --> 18:33.196
I understand you're considering
undergoing surgery to repair your wrist.

18:33.279 --> 18:34.322
Yes.

18:34.405 --> 18:38.451
As your oncologist, I need to strongly
urge you against that course of treatment.

18:38.535 --> 18:41.371
That's exactly what he said.
Did you tell her to say that?

18:41.454 --> 18:42.622
Absolutely not.

18:43.248 --> 18:47.460
DR. SINGH: Your immune system
is profoundly compromised by the chemo.

18:47.544 --> 18:50.171
The risk of postâ€“surgical infection
is very high.

18:50.255 --> 18:54.092
I advise against even minor surgery,
unless absolutely necessary.

18:54.175 --> 18:55.385
This is absolutely necessary

18:55.468 --> 18:57.887
because I'm making a Baked Alaska
for my daughter.

18:57.971 --> 19:01.099
And I cannot do that
with, like, a cast on my hand.

19:01.182 --> 19:04.394
Caroline, Robin would happily celebrate
her birthday

19:04.477 --> 19:06.646
with a supermarket cupcake
if she knew what the risks were.

19:06.729 --> 19:09.524
This isn't about what Robin wants.
This is about what I want.

19:11.484 --> 19:13.528
Why don't I give you two some privacy?

19:16.698 --> 19:17.699
What?

19:17.782 --> 19:21.452
How about we just have them put
a temp cast on it overnight.

19:21.536 --> 19:24.163
And then we can mull over the pluses
and the minuses...

19:24.247 --> 19:27.292
Dr. Charles? Sorry to interrupt,
but you've been requested down in the ED.

19:28.001 --> 19:29.002
(SIGHS)

19:29.085 --> 19:30.628
Yeah, they specifically asked
for you, Dr. Charles.

19:31.254 --> 19:33.965
Go, Daniel. Go, please.

19:37.218 --> 19:38.553
Heather?

19:38.636 --> 19:40.763
Can you do me a favor
and please try and make sure

19:40.847 --> 19:43.016
she does not get cleared
for surgery until I get back.

19:43.766 --> 19:44.893
Daniel...
Please.

19:44.976 --> 19:47.186
I just wanna make sure she doesn't make
any rash decisions.

19:47.270 --> 19:48.605
Thank you.

19:49.856 --> 19:50.857
(SIGHS)

19:50.940 --> 19:52.233
For the record,

19:52.317 --> 19:54.110
CCI neither condones nor endorses

19:54.193 --> 19:56.362
the preâ€“emptive precipitation
